<font color="#FF0000">BIRDMAN, FELLOW VET</font><br>
<tt>Mon Aug 18 20:47:32 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
OK BILL!!!!<br><br>
I have read your plea and have listened to Humming Eagle and the Others tell you like its is.  I am going to tell you I have not spent 8,000 hours turning Jp4 Jp5 Jp8 Jp7 and Jet A into hot air without learning a few things.  Few areas I haven't touched and no service I haven't flown for which includes the Navy and Marine Corp.  How about that Ed.<br><br>
I have stood in all those places you speak of and understand.<br><br>
First.  Everyone who served in the conflict was a veteran.  Do you think you would call one of the triple Nickel 555 out of Clark a non vet and live?  Nope.  What about all the fighter bases in Korat and Ubon and other areas?  Do you know of the Luzon group out of CCK or the Strat Recon group out of Kadena.  None of these places are in country but all had distinguished Vietnam Vets.  Do you think the Wild Weasels or the Wolf Pack were stationed in country?  Know  how many Navy and Marine pilots were stationed in the gulf?  Most fighter pilots.  Vets were everywhere, I hope I have proved my point.  YOU DIDN'T HAVE TO BE STATIONED IN COUNTRY TO BE A VIETNAM VET.  Any one who says this can just kiss our ass.<br><br>
Clark AB.  Just over 9000 ft of runway with a KC-135 take off weight of 258,000lbs on station at bingo + 90,000lbs.  Used every brick of runway to get that gas on station.  Takes no balls to roll into the overrun at 165kts looking for V2 does it.  Did you limp home at bingo minus at 40,000+?  That's the calls I used to hear, always out of gas because you couldn't bear to not give a guy that extra for mama.  Sound familiar.<br><br>
You think we didn't appreciate that act of selflessness.  You know what it was like to hear cleared to the contact position ready and see those captains bars flashing to bring us in.  Real comfort.  Always knew you would sneak on one pump to make sure we had the AR manifold open and not embarrass us by blowing us off the boom.  Many a fighter pilot would not have made it home without the gas.  They bingoed the target looking for the Texaco they knew would be there no matter what.  Trust because you were part of the team.  A fighting team, a real Vet.<br><br>
You guys were put up in the 555 squadron building and lived in the ROK compound, right.  Did you know that a sapper sniper fired a round at me and my co-pilot leaving that building in 1972 and we are only here because a Marine helo took the round and crashed in front of our face. (Don't tell Ed and Cook I'll never live it down)  Hell combat is where you find it.  Not getting shot doesn't mean you are not in danger.<br><br>
Lockborne AFB.  That crew died during an alert exercise when the wing reserve tank of another tanker sliced through the cockpit.  Bill it was tragic, but the reports said that nothing could be done.  I too have watched friends burn to death.  It is a burden we all carry and I will help you with yours as will we all.<br><br>
Your KC-135As are still with you.  Most were given new engines and served valiantly in Desert Storm.  They now call them KC-135 R models. Damn, now they better climb performance than an F4-C.  Bet your tail number is still active.  SAC is now part of the Tactical Air Command, which is an overhaul of all the warring airdales.  Navy was the last to fly A-models. (bet you didn't know that.  These birds are now in the bone yard.) <br><br>
There has been a lot of bases go by the way of the base closure list.  Your base among many.  Sad but an economic necessity of too few wars to fight.  The same is said of the RIF.  Happens after every conflict.  I am sorry you were cut.  They may have done you a favor.  You wouldn't have wanted to see the new service.  Nothings the same.<br><br>
Bill, you are among brothers that will help you along the way.  You area Vietnam VET and you suffer like the rest of us.  Accept that!!!!!<br><br>
As for the country.  Don't hate it.  It is great.  The politics suck and the politicians are devoid of brain power, but it is still the best thing going.  I have been the other places and know these things.  We must get you through your pain and help you to understand why we are proud to be the fighting men of a great country.<br><br>
Ok, Bill if you want to go down this path then lets go.  I have tried to show you that I can understand where you are coming from.  Trust Me and the others.  There is both Wisdom and Peace on this site.<br>

<p><code>--   (Silent Warrior) </code><p>


